            The chief security officer is to:






Security screening function



                  Lead and oversee the departmental security screening function to:




                      Enable the consistent and comprehensive conduct of security screening that:



                        Assesses the security screening requirements of positions, contracts or other arrangements;
                        Assesses the eligibility of an individual to hold a security or site access status, prior to a security or site access clearance;
                        Informs the decision-making process to grant, deny or revoke a security status or clearance, or site access status or clearance; and
                        Affords rights of review and redress that apply to all individuals, where a decision may be reached to deny, revoke or suspend a security status or clearance, or site access status or clearance;



                      Ensure that individuals:



                        Can be trusted to safeguard government information and assets, including information technology (IT) systems and facilities; and
                        Are aware of their security responsibilities;


                    Ensure departmental workforce awareness, capacity and capability to meet security screening function requirements, including respecting the values and principles of the Government of Canada;

                      Maintain a security file for all individuals for whom security screening is conducted in accordance with the 

                        Privacy Act

                       and associated Government of Canada policy instruments;


                      Ensure that personal information for the purpose of security screening is:




                          Collected, created, used, disclosed, retained and disposed of in accordance with the 

                            Privacy Act

                           and Government of Canada policy instruments;




                      Develop and implement processes to share information within the department and with other departments that:



                        Are defined and implemented;
                        Align with Government of Canada direction for managing security screening information;

                          Comply with the 

                            Privacy Act

                           and Government of Canada policy instruments for handling personal information;

                        Facilitate the transfer and acceptance of security screening files with other departments; and
                        Enable sharing of information within the department and with other departments, where a decision is reached to deny, revoke or suspend a security status or clearance or site access status or clearance;





                  When there is a requirement to conduct security screening of individuals external to government with whom the department has a need to share sensitive information or assets or to provide access to sensitive IT systems or facilities, ensure that:




                      Security screening requirements for contractors and other individuals are detailed in relevant documentation (see 
                      Appendix F: Mandatory Procedures for Security in Contracts and Other Arrangements Control
                       of the 

                        Directive on Security Management

                      ); and

                    The required security status or clearance is granted before information is shared and access is provided;








Interdepartmental security screening services



                  Use security screening services where mandated or available to meet the departmental security screening requirements; and



                    Ensure that the services obtained meet those requirements;



                  Ensure that a written agreement is in place when the organization provides or receives security screening services from another organization pursuant to subsections 6.3 and 6.4 that:



                    Defines applicable security and privacy requirements, in collaboration with responsible departmental officials; and
                    Establishes respective security screening responsibilities;



                  Where the security screening function involves the provision of services to client departments:



                    Confirm that security screening requirements of client department positions are developed under the direction of the chief security officer of the client department; and
                    Before recommending a decision to grant, grant with conditions, deny or revoke a security status or clearance, consult the chief security officer and, as appropriate, the deputy head, of the client department;








Security risk and adverse information



                  Take measures to address any security risk that presents serious and immediate threats to the security of persons, information or assets of the department or the Government of Canada and, when appropriate:



                    Consult with human resources management regarding the suspension of an employeeâs security status or clearance;

                      Consult with the contracting authority regarding the suspension of a contractorâs:



                        Security status or clearance; or
                        Site access status or clearance;


                    Suspend the security status or clearance or site access status or clearance of the individual, pending an investigation;
                    Revoke the security status or clearance or site access status or clearance of the individual, where they refuse to provide consent or withdraws consent 30 days after suspension; and

                      Report such security events to the appropriate law enforcement authority or security and intelligence agency (see 
                      Appendix I: Standard on Security Event Reporting
                       of the 

                        Directive on Security Management

                      );









Variation requests


                Support the deputy head to obtain the approval of the President of the Treasury Board of any temporary exception to the application of this directive and any supporting instruments, including standards, mandatory procedures and other appendices, in consultation with the Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat and other stakeholders;






Life-cycle management



                  Establish and oversee the implementation and review of security screening practices for positions and individuals:



                    Define, document, and implement departmental practices for the life cycle of position analysis and security screening; and
                    Coordinate with departmental human resources management practices;








Monitoring and reporting



                  Monitor compliance with this directive:



                    Assess, investigate and report any significant compliance issues to the deputy head; and
                    Take action as directed by the deputy head;



                  Document and monitor security screening practices to meet identified security requirements for programs, services and activities; and



                    Ensure ongoing adherence with security screening practices;


                Collaborate with senior officials and other stakeholders to respond to direction, advice and information requests issued by the Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat; and
                Provide information to the Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat upon request.

            Senior officials, designated by the deputy head in the departmental security governance, are to:






Security screening function


                Participate in and report to the departmental security governance;

                  Collaborate with senior officials, security functional specialists, partners and other stakeholders to:



                    Identify security screening requirements and related resource needs for programs, services and activities;
                    Document and implement security screening practices to meet identified security requirements for programs, services and activities;
                    Ensure ongoing adherence with security screening practices;
                    Assign security screening responsibilities for programs, services and activities;
                    Document and implement departmental security rights of review and redress practices for security screening activities; and
                    Provide advice to the deputy head, the chief security officer and other stakeholders on departmental security screening matters in their area of responsibility;








Interdepartmental security screening services



                  Where the security screening function involves the provision of services to, or relies upon, another department, ensure that:




                      Support is provided to the chief security officer in meeting subsection 4.1.4 of this directive so that:



                        Requirements and responsibilities of the agreement are met; and
                        Compliance is monitored;










Security risk and adverse information


                Address adverse information, in collaboration with the chief security officer, partners and other stakeholders; and






Monitoring and reporting


                Monitor and report on the effectiveness of security screening practices within their area of responsibility and share the results with the chief security officer.

Individuals who have human resources responsibilities are to:



  Integrate security screening considerations into planning and other administrative activities;

    Collaborate with the chief security officer to determine the appropriate screening level for each position for which they are responsible:




        In accordance with subsections A.2.2.4 and A.2.2.10 of 
        Appendix A: Standard on Security Screening Model and Position Analysis
        ;



  Ensure the established requirement of a security status or clearance as a condition of employment, appointment, contract or other arrangement, or assignment for positions for which they are responsible, is reflected in relevant documentation;

    Ensure that individuals for whom they are currently responsible or may become responsible have a valid security status or clearance, as defined by the departmentâs security screening requirements, before:



      Issuing an unconditional job offer;

        Awarding a contract; or



          During the pre-contractual phase, providing a contractor access to sensitive information for the purpose of bidding;


      Placing them in a position by means of other mechanisms such as an assignment, secondment, volunteer or other official capacity; and
      Providing access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;


  Ensure that individuals for whom they are responsible have received a security briefing prior to providing access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities; and
  Report to the chief security officer changes in personal circumstances and behaviour of individuals for whom they are responsible, which may affect the security status or clearance they have been granted.

Individuals are to:



  Provide their consent to initiate screening activities;

    Provide the personal information and evidentiary documents required for security screening:



      Accurately and truthfully; and
      In accordance with the required format and established time frames and update cycles;



    Indicate their understanding and acceptance of security responsibilities by signing the 
    Security Screening Certificate and Briefing Form
    ;


    Perform their duties reliably and in compliance with:



      The security status or clearance they are granted;

        The security obligations detailed in the 
        Security Screening Certificate and Briefing Form
        ; and

      Government of Canada security policy and departmental security practices, including safeguarding information and assets under their control, whether working onsite or offsite;



    Notify their manager or chief security officer of the following:



      Information related to a change in personal circumstances;
      Any persistent or unusual contact, or any attempt by an individual, group, organization or other entity to solicit or obtain access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities, without authorization; or

        Behaviour of individuals that may present a security risk to the department or the Government of Canada (as described in 
        Appendix G: Mandatory Procedures for the Granting, Ongoing Maintenance and Assurance of the Security Screening of an Individual
        ).

Mandatory procedures are as follows:
Conduct security screening activities in accordance with Annex A1 and Annex A3 of Appendix A: Standard on Security Screening Position Analysis and Model as identified below:
Verify identity before undertaking any subsequent security screening activities; and Conduct all subsequent security screening activities in relation to the individual;
Identity verification practices
Verify evidence of identity in accordance with the Standard on Identity and Credential Assurance ; and
Apply identity and credential assurance level 3 as the minimum level required for all levels of security screening;
Background verification practices
Verify the accuracy of the background information provided by the individual through a risk-based approach:
Where it is not possible to verify all the required years of background information, consider:
Alternate sources of information, including but not limited to:
Â Â Additional references; and
Â Â Resolution of doubt in accordance with Appendix E: Mandatory Procedures for Resolution of Doubt and Review for Cause ;
Account for individuals who have lived outside of Canada for longer than six months consecutively within the time period required by the security status or clearance in the following ways:
A letter of reference or referral from a foreign embassy or mission in Canada;
A letter of reference or referral from a Canadian embassy or mission in the country or countries in which the individual resided;
A letter of reference from a foreign educational institution or university;
A letter or police clearance certificate from a law enforcement agency of jurisdiction in the country in which the individual resided;
A credit summary from an established foreign financial institution;
Employment or assignment with a Government of Canada department or agency or with the Canadian Armed Forces outside Canada;
Information from counterpart security screening organizations in countries with which Canada has entered into bilateral arrangements for the exchange of security screening information; or
Alternate sources of information that are sufficient to account for their activities and the associated risk;
Assess activities accounted for in one or more of these ways in consideration of the adequacy and reliability of the source;
Educational and professional credential verification
Verify relevant educational and professional credentials and designations;
Personal and professional reference checks
Verify information about the individual from persons who know or who are in a position to take notice of the individual;
Financial inquiry
Obtain a full consumer credit report from a credit reporting agency that:
Includes information on the credit history, liens, judgments or bankruptcy of the individual; and Excludes and does not negatively affect the credit score of the individual;
Where a reliable credit report from a credit reporting agency cannot be obtained, develop and administer a financial assessment questionnaire for individuals; and Apply the results of the financial inquiry to assess whether an individual poses a security risk on the basis of financial pressure or a history of poor financial responsibility;
Criminal records check
Obtain a criminal record check against the RCMPâs National Repository of Criminal Records to confirm the involvement of the individual in criminal activity;
Require individuals who have lived outside of Canada for longer than six months consecutively within the time period required by the security status or clearance to:
Â Obtain a police clearance certificate or equivalent documentation that provides:
A summary of an individualâs criminal record; or
A declaration of the absence of any criminal record;
Â Where a country of residence:
Does not provide police clearance certificates or equivalent documentation; or
Obtaining the documentation presents undue risk to the individual, consider:
Â Alternate sources of information, sufficient to:
Â Â Â Confirm the involvement or absence thereof, of the individual in criminal activity; and
Â Â Â Assess the risk associated with past criminal convictions;
Apply the results of criminal record checks and out-of-country documentation to assess the risk associated with past criminal convictions.
CSIS security assessment
Obtain a CSIS security assessment to:
Â Determine whether there is sufficient information available upon which to base a security screening decision; and
Â Assess, where sufficient information is available, whether there is reasonable cause to believe that the individual has engaged, is engaged or may engage in activities that constitute a âthreat to the security of Canada,â as defined in section 2 of the Canadian Security Intelligence Service Act ;
Internet inquiry
Review publicly available personal information on the Internet to:
Â Verify accuracy and integrity of the background information provided by the individual; and
Â Identify potential adverse information based on behaviours, conduct, associations, judgment or features of character;
Take reasonable steps to verify the accuracy of information obtained from the Internet inquiry;
Law enforcement records check
Obtain additional RCMP and jurisdictional police agency records to verify:
Â Outstanding warrants or prohibitions; and
Â Whether an individual has any associations with criminality or organized crime;
Security questionnaire or security interview
Develop and conduct a security questionnaire or a security interview that solicits information to:
Â Identify and validate adverse information;
Â Provide the individual an opportunity to explainadverse information; and
Â Assess security risk on the basis of ideology, conduct, associations, judgment, features of character and vulnerability to coercion;
Polygraph examination
Conduct a polygraph:
Â For positions that require an Enhanced Top Secret security clearance; or
Â Where necessary to comply with international information-sharing agreements entered into by the Government of Canada; and
Â To corroborate the results of security screening activities, including the absence of results;
Canadian citizenship verification
Verify Canadian citizenship for a Top Secret or Enhanced Top Secret security clearance:
Â In accordance with documents prescribed by the Government of Canada.

            Mandatory procedures are as follows:






Identity verification


                Administratively cancel the security screening process when identity information cannot be verified, despite reasonable and demonstrable effort.






Canadian citizenship verification


                Administratively cancel the security screening process when Canadian citizenship cannot be verified, despite reasonable and demonstrable effort, for Top Secret and Enhanced Top Secret security clearance.






Collective evaluation of security screening activities



                  Collectively evaluate the results of security screening activities:




                      Based on:



                        The quality, quantity, relevance, credibility and totality of the information available relative to the level of status or clearance being considered;
                        The contextual factors associated with the position, contract or other arrangement, including the totality of information related to the individual; and
                        Consider as a factor the presence of adverse information and information obtained through a resolution of doubt;



                      To assess:




                          Â 
                          The reliability of an individual, including their honesty and trustworthiness, based on whether they can be trusted to:



Safeguard information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;

Be relied upon to not abuse the level of trust accorded;

Perform the assigned duties in a manner that will reflect positively on the Government of Canada; and

Not pose a security risk to the Government of Canada;



                          Â 
                          Loyalty to Canada, as applicable, where there are reasonable grounds to believe that:




                              The individual has engaged, is engaged, may engage or may be induced to engage in activities that c

                                onstitute a threat to the security of Canada as defined in the 
                                Canadian Security Intelligence Service Act

                              ; or



                              In so far as it relates to reliability as it relates to loyalty: 




The individual has acted, is acting, may act or may be induced to act in a way that constitutes a threat to the security of Canada; or

The individual has disclosed, may disclose, may be induced to disclose or may cause to be disclosed sensitive information in a manner contrary to the public interest;




                            Consider the presence of information that supports the likelihood of these scenarios as the basis to deny a security clearance or Site Access clearance;
                            Consider the absence of adverse information pursuant to a CSIS security assessment as a factor in favour of whether to grant a security clearance or Site Access clearance; and
                            Consider insufficient information required for the CSIS security assessment as grounds upon which to deny a security clearance or Site Access clearance;












Identification and assessment of adverse information



                  Assess the significance of adverse information based on the specific details of that information and in light of the totality of an individualâs circumstances, including:



Mitigating and aggravating factors;

The nature of the adverse information;

The frequency of the adverse information;


                      The circumstances surrounding the adverse information, including; 



The impact of socio-economic and cultural factors as identified by the individual;



The severity of the adverse information;

The passage of time;

The duties to be performed;

Whether the individual has been forthcoming about the information; and

The remedial action and rehabilitation efforts of the individual;



                  Where an Internet inquiry uncovers potential adverse findings, before rendering a decision, provide the individual with the opportunity to:



                    Review a summary of the potential adverse findings; and
                    Explain the findings;



                  Deny a security status or clearance to an individual who cannot hold public office, contract or receive benefits under a contract pursuant to sections 750(2) and 750(3) of the 

                    Criminal Code

                  ;







Review and reporting of adverse information


                Review adverse information as a basis for further investigation, including a resolution-of-doubt interview; and
                Where the security screening function involves the provision of services to client departments, report adverse information to the chief security officer of the client department considering employment, appointment, contract or other arrangement, or assignment of the individual.

            Mandatory procedures are as follows:






Decision to grant



                  Consider a decision to grant when the collective evaluation of the security screening results of an individual indicates:



There is no credible evidence that casts doubt on the reliability of an individual and, as applicable, their loyalty to Canada; and

Adverse information that is uncovered during security screening has been addressed; and


                Render a decision to grant a security status or clearance at the time the security screening is processed;






Notification of a decision to grant


                Notify the individual of the decision to grant a security status or clearance through a security briefing;






Decision to grant with conditions


                Do not grant with conditions as a substitute to security screen individuals at the level required by the position;

                  Consider a decision to grant with conditions only when:



The conditions are deemed sufficient to mitigate the security risk of granting; and

There is a demonstrated need to engage the individual;



                  Impose conditions that formally detail restrictions attached to the granting of a security status or clearance, including:



                    Limits on the access to information and assets, including IT systems and facilities that are necessary to perform the assigned duties;

                      Where one or more of the following conditions applies:



Do not grant access to classified information from a foreign government without the written consent of that foreign government, subject to the provisions of any information-sharing agreements;

Do not grant access to classified information from other departments without consultation with those departments; or

The security status or clearance granted to the individual is not transferable to any other duty or position in the department or to any other department;



                      As required:



                        Supplemental monitoring and reporting requirements to provide added assurance of the ongoing reliability or loyalty of the individual to Canada;
                        Limit the access of the individual to information and assets, including IT systems and facilities, to during designated working hours only; or
                        Setting other reasonable conditions that are necessary to effectively manage departmental or Government of Canada security risks; and




                Reassess security conditions annually, at a minimum;






Notification of a decision to grant with conditions


                Notify the individual of the decision to grant a security status or clearance with conditions through a security briefing, including the nature of the conditions;
                Obtain acknowledgement from the individual of their security responsibilities, including the nature of the conditions; and
                Retain a record of the decision and acknowledgement in their security screening file;






Decision to suspend pending an investigation



                  Consider a decision to suspend a security status or clearance where:



An investigation is pending;


                      Information suggests that the continued presence of the individual may reasonably pose a security risk to others, the department or the Government of Canada; and



Alternate work arrangements are insufficient to address the security risk; or

The continued presence of an individual could undermine or impede the investigation;





                  Prior to rendering a decision to suspend a security status or clearance:




                      For an employee:




                          Â 
                          Consult with human resources management to ensure that the employerâs labour relations obligations are considered and addressed; and




                      For a contractor or other individual:




                          Â 
                          Inform the contracting authority before informing the contractor;











Notification of a decision to suspend



                  Inform the individual in writing of the action to be taken, including the following:



The decision to suspend the security status or clearance pending an investigation;

The reasons the security status or clearance is being suspended;

Any circumstances or contributing factors that were taken into consideration in reaching this decision;

The manner and time frame in which the suspension will be administered; and

The manner in which the individual may exercise the opportunity to respond to or challenge the action;








Decision to reinstate following a suspension



                  If a security status or clearance has been suspended for cause:




                      During the course of an investigation, consider the possibility of reinstatement:



When new facts or circumstances are identified; and

Within a reasonable period of time and periodically throughout the suspension;



                      Render a decision to reinstate or revoke based on:



Findings and recommendations from the investigation; and

The updated risk to the department or Government of Canada;










Notification of a decision to reinstate following a suspension


                Notify the employee of the decision to reinstate a security status or clearance, through a security briefing;






Decision to deny



                  Consider a decision to deny when there is credible evidence that casts doubt as to an individualâs:



Reliability and, as applicable, loyalty to Canada;

Ability to be trusted to safeguard sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;


                Inform the deputy head of a decision to deny a security clearance within five days after the decision is made;






Decision to revoke



                  Consider a decision to revoke:



                    Following an update, upgrade or a review for cause of the security status or clearance previously granted to an individual;

                      When there is credible evidence that casts doubt as to an individualâs:



Reliability and, as applicable, loyalty to Canada; and

Ability to be trusted to safeguard sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;





                  Prior to rendering a decision to revoke:



                    Consider the availability and feasibility of alternative options, including downgrading the status or clearance of an individual;

                      For an employee:




                          Â 
                          Consult with human resources management to ensure that the employerâs labour relations obligations are considered and addressed;




                      For a contractor or other individual:




                          Â 
                          Inform the contracting authority before informing the contractor; and



                    Consult the deputy head in the event of a dispute as to the appropriate action to be taken;



                  Following a decision to revoke:



                    Prior to informing the individual, ensure that measures are taken to prevent the individual from accessing sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;
                    Inform the deputy head of a decision to revoke a security clearance within five days after the decision is made;
                    For a contractor, inform the contracting authority before the contractor; and

                      Notify CSIS via form CSIS 4160 
                      Notification of Change in Security Clearance
                      ;









Notification of a decision to deny or revoke



                  Notify the individual of a decision to deny or revoke their security status or clearance:



                    Within 10 days after the decision is made;
                    In writing from the chief security officer or the deputy head;

                      Include the reasons for the decision and the information on which the decision is based:




                          Â 
                          Exclude information that cannot be disclosed:




                              Under the 

                                Privacy Act

                              ;


For reasons of national security; or

Under other federal legislation;




                    Inform the individual of their rights of review or redress.


                Following notification of the individual, inform CSIS of the decision to deny or revoke a security clearance.

The chief security officer and those with subordinate responsibilities must apply the mandatory procedures below as follows:
Security briefings
The security briefing must:
Involve the manager of the individual or security officials;
Inform the individual of their responsibilities under the
Policy on Government Security
, including at a minimum:
Access permissions attached to their screening level;
The security expectations related to their position, contract or other arrangement; and
Shared security responsibilities within the organization;
Be completed before an individual is provided access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;
Be conducted in these circumstances:
Following a decision to grant or grant with conditions;
Whenever a change occurs in the security screening level of the individual;
As required based on the update cycle as defined in at Annex G2 or Annex G3 ; and
As determined by the department based on its security risk environment;
Provide an opportunity for the individual to ask questions;
Include the signing of the Security Screening Certificate and Briefing Form by the individual; and
Be retained in the security screening file of the individual;
Inform CSIS when a security clearance is granted, via form CSIS 4195 Notification of Security Clearance ;
Security awareness
Conduct security awareness, in accordance with Appendix H: Mandatory Procedures for Security Awareness and Training Control of the
Directive on Security Management
, at minimum, as an outcome of the granting and updating phases of the security screening life cycle; and
Inform individuals of the requirement to report changes in personal circumstances, including at minimum the following:
Change in criminal record status;
Involvement with law enforcement;
Association with criminals; or
A significant change in financial situation;
Inform individuals who work in security or intelligence organizations of the requirements to report additional changes in their personal or legal status, including a change in marital status; and Inform managers how to report and to whom they are to report observed changes in behaviour of individuals for whom they are responsible;
Recurring activities
Review the security screening requirements of positions when new programs or activities are established or substantially modified and, at minimum, every five years; and:
Inform security screening service providers of any changes in requirements;
Conduct security screening activities for individual security screening files that meet the minimum frequencies, as prescribed in Annex G1 ;
Updates
Update the individualâs security screening prior to the end of their validity period, in addition to the conduct of recurring activities;
Re-examine the reliability or loyalty of an individual since the individual was last granted a security status or clearance:
Conduct the update process consistent with:
Security Screening update cycles and the activities identified in Annex G2 ; or
Site Access screening update cycles and the activities identified in Annex G3 ;
Evaluate whether changes in personal circumstances pose a security risk; Determine the continued eligibility of an individual to hold a security status or clearance, based on the collective evaluation of security screening activities; and Provide a security briefing to inform the individual of their security responsibilities consistent with subsections G.2.2.1 and G.2.2.3;
When an individual does not provide consent, withdraws consent or does not provide the required information, proceed in accordance with subsection B.2.2.5.2 of Appendix B: Mandatory Procedures for the Management of Personal Information for the Purpose of Security Screening ;
Repeat any security screening activity where:
Required by the update cycle; or
There is reason to believe:
The activities were conducted improperly; or
There is no documentation on the file of the initial conduct of the screening activities;
Upgrades
When upgrading a valid security status or clearance to a higher level:
Conduct additional security screening activities and years of background information required for the new level in accordance with Annex A1 of Appendix A: Standard on Security Screening Model and Position Analysis ;
Determine the eligibility of an individual to hold the new security status or clearance, based on the collective results of all security screening activities; and Provide a security briefing to inform the individual of their security responsibilities consistent with subsections G.2.2.1 and G.2.2.3
Where an individual does not provide consent, withdraws consent or does not provide the required information, proceed in accordance with subsection B.2.2.5.1 of Appendix B: Mandatory Procedures for the Management of Personal Information for the Purpose of Security Screening ;
Downgrades
When downgrading a valid status or clearance to a lower level:
Provide a security briefing to inform the individual of their security responsibilities consistent with subsections G.2.2.1 and G.2.2.3;
Â Which includes informing individuals and managers that the individual may no longer access higher levels of sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities;
Security debriefing
The security debriefing must:
Be provided to individuals, prior to the end of employment or engagement with the department; Advise individuals of their continued responsibilities to maintain the confidentiality of the sensitive information to which they had access; and
Use the Security Screening Certificate and Briefing Form to record:
Completion of the debriefing; or
Where it is impossible to debrief the individual;
Â Be retained in the security screening file of the individual in accordance with subsection B.2.2.18 of Appendix B: Mandatory Procedures for the Management of Personal Information for the Purpose of Security Screening .

            Mandatory procedures for chief security officers are as follows:






Decision to provide temporary access to sensitive information or assets


                Do not consider a decision to provide temporary access when it is expected that access will be required for longer than four months;
                Do not consider a decision to provide temporary access as a substitute to security screen individuals at the level required by the position;

                  Consider a decision to provide the individual with temporary access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems or facilities:



                    Where there is an operational requirement for this individual that cannot be performed by another with a valid security screening at the required level; and
                    Where a risk assessment demonstrates that the need to provide the individual with temporary access outweighs the risk associated with providing the individual access


                Impose restrictions that detail limits to accessing sensitive information and assets, including IT systems or facilities to which the temporary access provision includes;






Notification of a decision to provide temporary access



                  Notify the individual of the decision to provide temporary access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities through a security briefing, including:



                    The duration of the access; and
                    The provisions of the access;



                  For the agreement of temporary access:



                    Obtain the signature of the individual receiving access;
                    Obtain the signature of the custodian of the information to be accessed;
                    Sign the agreement; and
                    Include the agreement in the security screening file of the individual;








Notification of a decision to remove temporary access



                  Debrief the individual following the removal of temporary access, including:



                    Advise the individual of their continued responsibilities to maintain the confidentiality of the sensitive information to which they had access;
                    Include a copy of the signed agreement in the security screening file of the individual; and
                    Retain evidence of the debriefing in the security screening file of the individual;








Managing temporary access of the individual



                  When temporary access is granted:




                      Prevent the individual from accessing:



Compartmented information;

Enhanced Top Secret information;

Protected C information

Information for which access is restricted in accordance with international agreements or special caveats;

Cabinet documents as defined within the Government of Canada, the Privy Council Office or the Policy on the Security of Cabinet Confidences;

Sensitive information from other governments and levels of government; and

Sensitive information, assets, IT systems and facilities from other departments without their documented approval


                    Maintain positive control of access to sensitive information and assets, including IT systems and facilities to which the temporary access provision includes.
